Any.description:
`Any` contains an arbitrary serialized message along with a
URL that describes the type of the serialized message

@type.description: A URL/resource name that uniquely identifies the type of the serialized message.

DiscountCurveConfigDiscountCurveType.description:
- DISCOUNT_CURVE_TYPE_UNSPECIFIED: Default value
 - DISCOUNT_CURVE_TYPE_NAME: Represents an input specified in Discount Curve Name
 - DISCOUNT_CURVE_TYPE_CLIENT: Indicates that the curve is a client curve
DiscountCurveConfigDiscountCurveType.title: DiscountCurve enum

EconomyConfigEconomyType.description:
- ECONOMY_TYPE_UNSPECIFIED: Unspecified value
 - ECONOMY_TYPE_END_OF_DAY: Represents valuation using end of day economy data as per economy date specified
This is the default economy which will be used for valuation
 - ECONOMY_TYPE_INTRA_DAY: Represents valuation using intra day economy data as per time specified
EconomyConfigEconomyType.title: Economy types available for valuation

FaceAmountConfigFaceType.description:
- FACE_TYPE_UNSPECIFIED: Default value
 - FACE_TYPE_ORIGINAL: Represents an input of Original Face
 - FACE_TYPE_CURRENT: Represents an input of Current Face
FaceAmountConfigFaceType.title: Face types available to be specified

InflationConfigInflationProjectionType.description:
- INFLATION_PROJECTION_TYPE_UNSPECIFIED: Default value
 - INFLATION_PROJECTION_TYPE_GOVERNMENT_TERM_STRUCTURE: Represents an input to use Government Term Structure
 - INFLATION_PROJECTION_TYPE_SWAP_TERM_STRUCTURE: Represents an input to use Swap Term Structure
 - INFLATION_PROJECTION_TYPE_CONSTANT: Represents a constant inflation rate
InflationConfigInflationProjectionType.title: Inflation projection types available for valuation

InterestRateShockInterestRateShockInputT.description:
- INTEREST_RATE_SHOCK_INPUT_TYPE_UNSPECIFIED: Default value
 - INTEREST_RATE_SHOCK_INPUT_TYPE_PARALLEL: Represents an input of parallel shock
 - INTEREST_RATE_SHOCK_INPUT_TYPE_STANDARD: Represents an input of standard shock
 - INTEREST_RATE_SHOCK_INPUT_TYPE_CUSTOM: Represents an input of custom shock
 - INTEREST_RATE_SHOCK_INPUT_TYPE_USER: Represents an input of user shock
InterestRateShockInterestRateShockInputT.title: Settlement types available to be specified

PricingConfigPricingInputType.description:
- PRICING_INPUT_TYPE_UNSPECIFIED: Default value
 - PRICING_INPUT_TYPE_PRICE: Represent an input which is a direct price
 - PRICING_INPUT_TYPE_SHORTCUT: Represents an input specified in shortcut form
PricingConfigPricingInputType.title: Pricing input types available to be specified

SettlementConfigSettlementType.description:
- SETTLEMENT_TYPE_UNSPECIFIED: Default value
 - SETTLEMENT_TYPE_DATE: Represents an input in form of a custom date
 - SETTLEMENT_TYPE_CONVENTION: Represents an input in form of settlement convention
Such as DEF/SAME/T+1
SettlementConfigSettlementType.title: Settlement types available to be specified

ValuationModeConfigValuationMode.description:
- VALUATION_MODE_UNSPECIFIED: Unspecified value
 - VALUATION_MODE_DEFAULT_SETTINGS: Value representing default valuation Mode
ValuationModeConfigValuationMode.title: Valuation Modes available for analysis

rpcStatus.description:
The `Status` type defines a logical error model that is suitable for
different programming environments, including REST APIs and RPC APIs. It is
used by [gRPC](https://github.com/grpc). Each `Status` message contains
three pieces of data: error code, error message, and error details.

You can find out more about this error model and how to work with it in the
[API Design Guide](https://cloud.google.com/apis/design/errors).

code.description: The status code, which should be an enum value of [google.rpc.Code][google.rpc.Code].

message.description:
A developer-facing error message, which should be in English. Any
user-facing error message should be localized and sent in the
[google.rpc.Status.details][google.rpc.Status.details] field, or localized by the client.

details.description:
A list of messages that carry the error details.  There is a common set of
message types for APIs to use.

v1LongrunningOperation.description:
LongrunningOperation represents a long-running operation that is the result
of a network API call.

id.description:
The server-assigned id, which is only unique within the same service that
originally returns it. If you use the default HTTP mapping, the
`id` should have the format of `operations/some/unique/id`.

meta.description:
Service-specific metadata associated with the operation.  It typically
contains progress information and common metadata such as create time.
Some services might not provide such metadata.  Any method that returns a
long-running operation should document the metadata type, if any.

done.description:
If the value is `false`, it means the operation is still in progress.
If true, the operation is completed, and either `error` or `response` is
available.

error.description: The error result of the operation in case of failure or cancellation.

response.description:
The normal response of the operation in case of success.  If the original
method returns no data on success, such as `Delete`, the response is
`google.protobuf.Empty`.  If the original method is standard
`Get`/`Create`/`Update`, the response should be the resource.  For other
methods, the response should have the type `XxxResponse`, where `Xxx`
is the original method name.  For example, if the original method name
is `TakeSnapshot()`, the inferred response type is
`TakeSnapshotResponse`.
